Currently the `instrsxarch.h` macros define a number of pieces of information for each instruction:
* id
* name
* update mode
* encodings
* flags
  * is floating point
  * reads flags
  * writes flags

The `flags` are currently listed separately and combined later:
```cpp
// ...
#define INST5(id, nm, fp, um, rf, wf, mr, mi, rm, a4, rr)
// ...
INST5(push   , "push"         , 0, IUM_RD, 0, 0, 0x0030FE, 0x000068, BAD_CODE, BAD_CODE, 0x000050)
```
and
```cpp
const BYTE          CodeGenInterface::instInfo[] =
{
    // ...
    #define INST5(id, nm, fp, um, rf, wf, mr, mi, rm, a4, rr ) (INST_USE_FL*rf|INST_DEF_FL*wf|INST_FP*fp),
    // ...
};
```

I propose we refactor this so that all flags are listed together, under a single macro parameter. This would help facilitate the ability to insert additional flags, as necessary:
```cpp
#define INST5(id, nm, um, flags, mr, mi, rm, a4, rr)
INST5(push   , "push"         , IUM_RD, INS_FLAGS_None,        0x0030FE, 0x000068, BAD_CODE, BAD_CODE, 0x000050)
INST5(inc    , "inc"          , IUM_RW, INS_FLAGS_WritesFlags, 0x0000FE, BAD_CODE, BAD_CODE, BAD_CODE, 0x000040)
```
and
```
const insFlags          CodeGenInterface::instInfo[] =
{
    // ...
    #define INST5(id, nm, um, flags, mr, mi, rm, a4, rr ) static_cast<insFlags>(flags),
    // ...
};
```

Sometime there is a need to subscribe to `INotifyPropertyChanged.PropertyChanged` event of a model from another view model, e.g. logging of property changes of the model from the view model. Current `PropertyChangedEventArgs` does not have a `OldValue` and `NewValue` property for this purpose.

### **Proposal: Add OldValue & NewValue properties**

    public class PropertyChangedEventArgs : EventArgs
    {
        // Properties.
        public string PropertyName { get; set; }
        public object OldValue { get; set; }
        public object NewValue { get; set; }

        // ctor.
        public PropertyChangedEventArgs(string propertyName, object oldValue = null, object newValue = null)
        {
            PropertyName = propertyName;
            OldValue = oldValue;
            NewValue = newValue;
        }
    }


With the above changes, it will be possible for the model to raise `PropertyChanged` event in the property setter.

    public class Foo : INotifyPropertyChanged
    {
        // Fields.
        private DateTime m_CurrentDateTime;
        // Binding Properties.
        public DateTime CurrentDateTime
        {
            get
            {
                return m_CurrentDateTime;
            }
            set
            {
                if (!DateTime.Equals(m_CurrentDateTime, value))
                {
                    var oldValue = m_CurrentDateTime;
                    m_CurrentDateTime = value;
                    OnPropertyChanged(oldValue, value);
                }
            }
        }
        // Methods.
        private void OnPropertyChanged(object oldValue, object newValue, [CallerMemberName]string propertyName = "")
        {
            var arg = new PropertyChangedEventArgs(propertyName, oldValue, newValue);
            PropertyChanged?.Invoke(this, arg);
        }

        // ctor.
        public Foo()
        {
        }

        // INotifyPropertyChange.
        public event PropertyChangedEventHandler PropertyChanged;
    }
`

**Proposal**
Value arrays which can be determined as non-mutating can be singleton allocated. In the attached sample, this could be done by storing the array passed to `DoesNotMutate` as a static or other non-local context.

This proposal is to have value arrays which can be determined by the compiler as non-mutating be promoted to a static scope to prevent reallocation.

Because of the behavior of strings, this behavior should also happen for static strings.

One issue is it's possible the developer may have an extremely large array that would be undesirable to keep in memory. The promotion could have an upper limit on memory size.

```CSharp
using System;

namespace NS
{
    class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            for (var i = 0; i < 10; ++i)
            {
                DoesNotMutate(new[] { 1, 2 });
                DoesMutate(new[] { 2, 1 });
            }
        }
        
        static bool DoesNotMutate(int[] array)
        {
            return array.Length == 2;
        }
        
        static void DoesMutate(int[] array)
        {
            if (array.Length == 2)
            {
                array[0] = 3;
            }
        }
    }
}
```

**Desire Behavior**:

1 allocation of `[1, 2]` and 10 allocations of `[2, 1]` occur.

**Actual Behavior**:

10 allocations of `[1, 2]` and 10 allocations of `[2, 1]` occur.
